#combine all files in the list
combined_csv = pd.concat([pd.read_csv(f) for f in all_filenames ])
#export to csv
combined_csv.to_csv( "combined_2018.csv", index=False, encoding='utf-8-sig')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • here i am working with data from three consecutive yeas 2017, 2018 and 2019 seperated in three files. all files have common columns which is: bike_id
    duration_sec
    end_station_id
    end_station_latitude
    end_station_longitude
    end_station_name
    end_time
    start_station_id
    start_station_latitude
    start_station_longitude
    start_station_name
    start_time
    user_type(Subscriber or Customer – “Subscriber” = Member or “Customer” = Casual)

  • for 2017 recoreds, there are 519700 clints, 1863721 in 2018 and 2506983 in 2019.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

the features of interests are the ones related to the duration of trips, start trip stations, am also interested in kowing the user type Subscriber or Customer and its relation to other features like trip duration and at what time in term of day, week and months. in addition, is there a most frequent station used by users.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

From the dataset i will use in this analysis duration_sec, start_time, user_type, start_station_name.

Univariate Exploration¶

1- Numbers of users per month¶

Here is a bar chart showing the number of users per month in each year. the year 2019 has the highest number of clints of almost 250000 in March and July. In 2018, October had the highest number of clints of 200000. in 2017, its clear that the data start from June with October having the highest number of counts. in all three years, there are no trends or common months where it shows increases or decreases in bike raiders in the numbers of three years.
